# Deployment TODO

## Strategy

- Production only (no staging) — solo developer, early phase
- PR preview deployments come free from Cloudflare Pages (acts as "staging" for frontend)
- API doesn't have preview envs — local testing + CI is sufficient for now
- Add a proper staging environment later if/when needed (separate Railway project)
- Everything is env-var driven — no code changes needed to switch domains or services

## Domain Plan

Using kankava.com subdomains for now (no dedicated domain yet):

  mtamta.kankava.com       → Cloudflare Pages (web app)
  api.mtamta.kankava.com   → Railway (Go API)

When you buy a real domain (mtamta.com or whatever), just:
1. Add the new domain to Cloudflare
2. Point mtamta.com → Cloudflare Pages, api.mtamta.com → Railway
3. Update WEB_ORIGIN env var on Railway (CORS)
4. Update VITE_API_URL on Cloudflare Pages
5. Update Google OAuth redirect URIs
No code changes needed.

Alternative: skip custom domains entirely and use free defaults:
  - Web: mtamta.pages.dev (Cloudflare Pages)
  - API: api-production-xxxx.up.railway.app (Railway)

---

## Steps

### 1. Sign up for services

Accounts needed (all have free tiers):

  Mapbox      — mapbox.com — map tiles, styles, terrain — create a public token (pk.*)
  Railway     — railway.com — Go API + PostgreSQL + Redis — link your GitHub account
  Cloudflare  — cloudflare.com — web hosting (Pages) + DNS — free plan works

Google OAuth (needed for auth):
  - Google Cloud Console → create OAuth 2.0 credentials
  - Add authorized redirect URIs for your production domain

### 2. Push code to GitHub

  git branch -m master main
  git remote add origin git@github.com:kankava/mtamta.git
  git push -u origin main

### 3. Set up Railway

  1. Create a new project on Railway
  2. Add 3 services:
     - api — connect your GitHub repo, it'll use railway.toml + Dockerfile automatically
     - postgres — add TimescaleDB plugin (or use timescale/timescaledb-ha:pg17 Docker image)
     - redis — add the Redis plugin (managed)
  3. Set environment variables on the api service:
     - ENV=production
     - DATABASE_URL — Railway auto-injects this if you link postgres
     - REDIS_URL — auto-injected if you link redis
     - JWT_SECRET — generate a strong random string
     - GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID — from Google Cloud Console
     - APPLE_CLIENT_ID — skip for now if you don't have one
     - ALLOWED_EMAILS — your email (e.g. you@gmail.com) to restrict sign-ups to only you
     - WEB_ORIGIN — e.g. https://mtamta.kankava.com (or https://mtamta.pages.dev)
  4. Get your RAILWAY_TOKEN from Railway → Account Settings → Tokens

### 4. Set up Cloudflare Pages

  1. Go to Cloudflare Dashboard → Pages → Create a project
  2. Connect your GitHub repo
  3. Build settings:
     - Build command: pnpm turbo build --filter=@mtamta/web
     - Build output directory: apps/web/dist
     - Root directory: / (monorepo root)
  4. Environment variables:
     - VITE_API_URL — your Railway API URL (e.g. https://api.mtamta.kankava.com or the Railway default URL)
     - VITE_GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID — same as backend
     - VITE_MAPBOX_ACCESS_TOKEN — your Mapbox public token (pk.*)
     - NODE_VERSION = 22
  5. Get your CLOUDFLARE_ACCOUNT_ID (from dashboard URL) and create a CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN with Pages edit permissions

### 5. Configure custom domains (optional — can use defaults first)

  If using kankava.com subdomains:
  1. kankava.com DNS must be on Cloudflare (or add CNAME records wherever DNS is hosted)
  2. Add mtamta.kankava.com as custom domain on Cloudflare Pages project
  3. Add api.mtamta.kankava.com as custom domain on Railway api service
  4. Update WEB_ORIGIN on Railway and VITE_API_URL on Cloudflare Pages to match

### 6. Add GitHub Actions secrets

  Repo → Settings → Secrets and variables → Actions:

  RAILWAY_TOKEN          — from Railway
  CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN   — from Cloudflare
  CLOUDFLARE_ACCOUNT_ID  — from Cloudflare dashboard

### 7. Push to main and watch it deploy

  CI pipeline (.github/workflows/ci.yml) will:
  1. Run all tests (Go + TypeScript)
  2. Lint everything
  3. Build the web app
  4. Deploy API to Railway
  5. Deploy web to Cloudflare Pages

### 8. Post-deploy verification

  - Hit https://<your-api-url>/api/v1/health — should return 200
  - Open your web URL — should show the map
  - Test Google OAuth login flow end-to-end

